1. Create a .cpp File

You can use any text editor to create the file. Common editors include nano, vim, or graphical ones like gedit.
Using nano

    Open a terminal.
    Create a new file using:

nano myprogram.cpp

Write your C++ code in the editor.
Save the file:

    Press Ctrl + O, then press Enter.
    Exit by pressing Ctrl + X.
    
    
    
    
    
    
    /////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
    
    
    Compile the .cpp File

Use the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) to compile your file. The g++ command is used for C++ programs.

    Compile the program:

    g++ myprogram.cpp -o myprogram

        myprogram.cpp is your source file.
        -o myprogram specifies the name of the output binary.

    If the file has no errors, it will create an executable named myprogram.

4. Run the Compiled Program

To run the program:

./myprogram

Example
Write a Simple Program

    Create the file:

nano hello.cpp

Add the following code:

    #include <iostream>
    using namespace std;

    int main() {
        cout << "Hello, World!" << endl;
        return 0;
    }

    Save and exit.

Compile and Run

    Compile the file:

g++ hello.cpp -o hello

Run the program:

./hello

Output:

    Hello, World!

Tips

    If you encounter errors during compilation, read the error messages and fix your code accordingly.
    If g++ is not installed, install it using:

    sudo apt update
    sudo apt install g++


